SECTION 7.8 — DETERMINISTIC DECISION COMMUNICATION LAYER

7.8 — Deterministic Decision Communication Layer
7.8.0 Purpose & Scope
This section defines the structural communication architecture used when the platform presents interpretive outputs to travelers.
It governs:
●How decisions are structured
●How clause alignment is communicated
●How conflicts are presented
●How exclusions are framed
●How next steps are delivered
●How authority boundaries are stated
This section does not govern:
●Emotional tone (see Section 7.2 — Calm Mode Language System)
●Confidence scoring definitions (see Section 9.2 — Confidence Labels & Uncertainty Language)
●Visual layout or component design (see Section 7.7)
●Logging or enforcement logic (see Section 8.4)
●Decision logic itself (see Sections 3.4 and 6.5.x)
This section ensures that all decision outputs are deterministic, clause-bound, and structurally consistent.

7.8.1 Core Structural Formula (Mandatory)
All interpretive outputs must follow this order:
1.Recorded Fact
2.Clause Comparison
3.Structural Alignment or Conflict
4.Concrete Next Step
5.Boundary Statement
This structure must be preserved across:
●Coverage Graph outputs (6.5.2)
●Claim Routing (6.5.5)
●Credit Card Benefit Orchestration (6.5.4 / 6.5.7)
●Case study generation
●Crisis-related evaluations

7.8.2 Structural Authority Vocabulary
Approved Alignment Language
●“This aligns with the stated criteria under Section X.”
●“No exclusion is indicated under the reviewed sections.”
●“An exclusion applies under Section X.”
●“This does not meet the stated threshold at this time.”
●“This assessment reflects the current documentation.”
Prohibited Language
●“You qualify.”
●“You’re covered.”
●“Guaranteed.”
●“Best option.”
●“Very likely to win.”
Structural alignment is communicated without predictive payout language.

7.8.3 Boundary Statement Standard
All interpretive outputs must include a single boundary statement:
“Final review is performed by the benefit administrator.”
This statement must:
●Appear once per interpretive output
●Not undermine structural clarity
●Not appear as a hedge before alignment is explained

7.8.4 Causality Communication
When cause is not established:
“The available documentation does not establish a confirmed cause at this time.”
When conflict exists:
“Carrier documentation and the recorded timeline are in conflict.”
Causality language must remain structural and non-speculative.
See Section 3.4 — Causality Model.

7.8.5 Ambiguity Communication
Ambiguity must be surfaced with context:
“The term ‘X’ is not defined in the policy. Prior interpretations have varied.”
Ambiguity must not be expressed as:
●“Unclear.”
●“We’re not sure.”
Ambiguity detection occurs during policy parsing.

